{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1fff4f60-9cc2-417b-94f5-4b05edca5fcf","content":"## What Changed\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, **implicit span conversions** now participate in overload resolution. This causes `array.Contains(num)` to resolve to:\n\n```\nMemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(this ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)\n```\n\ninstead of the .NET 9 resolution:\n\n```\nEnumerable.Contains<T>(this IEnumerable<T>, T)\n```\n\n`ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a ref struct, and the expression tree **interpreter** (`preferInterpretation: true`) cannot handle the `int[]` → `ReadOnlySpan<int>` conversion at runtime, so it throws.\n\n## Fix\n\nDisambiguate so the compiler binds to `Enumerable.Contains`:\n\n```csharp\n// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n\n// Option 2: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nEither approach forces the old overload and restores the previous runtime behavior.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4eebf710-78cc-4689-8e5b-c73327267e68","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays, specifically when using `preferInterpretation: true`.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to extension methods. C# 14 introduces **extension types** (formerly \"roles and extensions\"), but more relevantly, there's a change in how the compiler resolves `Enumerable.Contains()` vs array-specific methods.\n \nI'm reconsidering what the actual breaking change might be—it could involve arrays gaining new built-in `Contains` methods through interface implementations or span-related changes in .NET 10, which would alter how expression trees are constructed compared to previous versions. The issue is that `MemoryExtensions.Contains` works with `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, which are ref structs that can't be represented in expression trees, so if the compiler is now resolving `.Contains()` to this method in .NET 10, the expression tree would fail at runtime when it tries to interpret a method it can't represent. But since the user says it throws at runtime rather than compile time, something about the method resolution must have changed in .NET 10 in a way that breaks the expression tree interpretation. The expression tree compiles fine but throws at runtime when interpreted, which suggests the issue isn't about compilation but about how the interpreter handles the method call. I'm reconsidering whether this is about overload resolution changes—maybe in .NET 10, `T[]` now implements additional interfaces like `IReadOnlyList<T>` that could affect which `Contains` overload gets selected and whether the expression tree interpreter can handle it. So the real issue is that when building expression trees manually with `Expression.Call`, the compiler can't handle `ReadOnlySpan<T>` parameters since expression trees don't support ref structs, causing a runtime failure when the tree tries to interpret or compile that method call. might be hitting a different issue. But the code shown uses a lambda assigned to `Expression<Func<...>>`, which would be caught at compile time if the expression tree couldn't represent it.\n\nWait - re-reading the user's code:\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr = (array, num) => array.Contains(num);\n```\n\nIf in C# 14 the compiler resolves `.Contains()` to `MemoryExtensions.Contains`, this would be a **compile-time error** because expression trees can't contain calls involving ref structs. The user says it \"throws at runtime\" though.\n\nUnless... the user is building the expression tree programmatically (the shown code is just illustrative), or unless there's a different issue.\n\nActually, wait. Let me reconsider. Maybe the issue is different. Let me think about what changed in .NET 10 specifically regarding the expression tree interpreter.\n\nI might be overcomplicating this. The real issue could be that .NET 10 changed how the expression tree interpreter handles certain method calls, or there's a specific optimization in `Enumerable.Contains` that the interpreter doesn't support. Let me trace back to what's most likely causing a runtime failure in .NET 10 with expression trees. is:\n\n**C# 14's new overload resolution (possibly related to extension types or span-based extensions) causes `array.Contains(num)` to bind to a different method.**\n\nActually, I just recalled something important. In .NET 10 Preview announcements, there was discussion about **implicit span conversions** being enabled more broadly. Specifically:\n\n- C# 14 adds first-class span support, including implicit conversions from `T[]` to `ReadOnlySpan<T>` in more contexts\n- This can change overload resolution so that `MemoryExtensions.Contains` (which takes `ReadOnlySpan<T>`) becomes preferred over `Enumerable.Contains` (which takes `IEnumerable<T>`)\n\nIf the compiler now binds to `MemoryExtensions.Contains`:\n- For regular code (not expression trees), this is fine and more efficient\n- For expression trees (`Expression<Func<...>>`), this would be a **compile-time error** because you can't put ref struct operations in expression trees\n\nBut if it's a compile-time error, the user's claim about a runtime throw doesn't add up. Maybe they're building the expression tree programmatically with `Expression.Call` targeting `Enumerable.Contains`, or perhaps the lambda still compiles to an expression tree in C# 14 but something about how that method behaves in .NET 10 is causing the runtime failure. I think I've been overcomplicating this. The real issue is likely that C# 14 introduced implicit span conversions that change how overload resolution works—so `array.Contains(num)` now re