y though, the compiler still targets `Enumerable.Contains` when building expression trees, but something about the method signature or overload resolution changed in .NET 10, causing the runtime failure. runtime error. The fix is to disambiguate.\n\nWait, I just realized something. Let me re-read the question: \"After upgrading to .NET 10 / C# 14, this throws at runtime.\"\n\nMaybe the code was pre-compiled (the expression tree was generated at build time with the new compiler) and the new method binding is what causes the runtime failure. If the expression tree now references `MemoryExtensions.Contains<int>(ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)`, and when you call `.Compile(preferInterpretation: true)`, the expression tree interpreter encounters a method that takes a `ReadOnlySpan<T>` parameter, and it can't handle the `int[]` → `ReadOnlySpan<int>` conversion, it would throw at runtime.\n\nActually, I think the issue is that the expression tree compiler succeeds in C# 14, but the interpreter fails because it doesn't support implicit span conversions at runtime—the JIT compiler handles them fine, but the simpler interpreter path doesn't. So when `preferInterpretation: true` is used, it can't convert the array to a span on the fly like the full JIT would.\n\nThe solution is to force the compiler to use `Enumerable.Contains` instead by casting to `IEnumerable<int>` or calling the method explicitly, which avoids the span conversion altogether.","outputTokens":4899,"requestId":"984D:F5EE8:90D48:B6493:69F54A7B"},"id":"e9ef8cb6-fad2-4cbd-9c44-9f587e7bd56c","timestamp":"2026-05-02T00:52:42.099Z","parentId":"76892b36-0009-4af1-8bf1-73a9f95c8473"}
